            principle: "A term will not be implied into a contract simply because it seems reasonable or fair. For a term to be implied to give business efficacy, it must be necessary for the contract to work, be so obvious it 'goes without saying', capable of clear expression, and not contradict any express terms. An unforeseen event that makes performance radically different from what was contemplated might lead to frustration rather than an implied term to cover the new situation.",
