            case: "Hamilton v Lethbridge (1912) 14 CLR 236",
            principle: "A contract of service (e.g., apprenticeship, employment) entered into by a minor will be binding on the minor if, when viewed as a whole, the contract is for the minor's benefit, even if it contains some clauses that, taken in isolation, might be prejudicial.",
            principle_zh: "未成年人订立的服务合同（例如，学徒合同、雇佣合同），如果从整体上看对未成年人有利，即使其中包含某些孤立看待可能不利的条款，该合同对未成年人也具有约束力。",
            summary: "Lethbridge, a minor, entered into articles of clerkship (an apprenticeship) with Hamilton, a solicitor. The contract contained a clause restraining Lethbridge from practising as a solicitor within 50 miles of Hamilton's practice after qualifying. On qualifying, Lethbridge set up practice within that area. Hamilton sought an injunction. The High Court held that, looking at the contract as a whole (which provided training and qualification for a profession), it was beneficial to Lethbridge and therefore binding on him, including the restraint clause.",
            summary_zh: "未成年人莱斯布里奇与律师汉密尔顿签订了见习文员合同（学徒合同）。合同中包含一项条款，限制莱斯布里奇在取得执业资格后，不得在汉密尔顿执业地点50英里范围内从事律师业务。取得资格后，莱斯布里奇在该区域内开设了律师事务所。汉密尔顿申请禁制令。高等法院认为，从整体上看该合同（为莱斯布里奇提供了专业培训和资格），对其有利，因此对他具有约束力，包括该限制条款。",
            scaffold: "Hamilton v Lethbridge demonstrates that a minor can be bound by a contract of service if the contract, taken as a whole, is for their benefit, even with some restrictive clauses.",
            scaffold_zh: "汉密尔顿诉莱斯布里奇案表明，如果服务合同从整体上看对未成年人有利，即使包含一些限制性条款，未成年人也可能受其约束。",
