            case: "De Francesco v Barnum (1890) 45 ChD 430",
            principle: "A contract of service with a minor, even if for training or employment, will not be considered beneficial and thus not binding on the minor if its terms are oppressive, unduly harsh, or unreasonable when viewed as a whole.",
            principle_zh: "与未成年人签订的服务合同，即使是为了培训或就业，如果其条款从整体上看具有压迫性、过于苛刻或不合理，则不会被视为对未成年人有利，因此对未成年人不具约束力。",
            summary: "A 14-year-old girl (Barnum) entered a 7-year apprenticeship with De Francesco to learn stage dancing. The contract terms were very restrictive: she could not marry, had no guarantee of work or pay when unemployed, was paid very little when working, and De Francesco could terminate at his discretion without her having a similar right. She took another engagement, and De Francesco sued. The court held the contract was unenforceable against the minor as its terms were oppressive and not, on balance, beneficial to her.",
            summary_zh: "14岁的女孩巴纳姆与德·弗朗切斯科签订了一份为期7年的学徒合同，学习舞台舞蹈。合同条款非常严格：她不能结婚，失业期间没有工作或工资保障，工作时工资很低，而且德·弗朗切斯科可以自行决定终止合同，而她没有类似的权利。她接受了另一份工作邀约，德·弗朗切斯科因此起诉。法院认为该合同对未成年人不具强制执行力，因为其条款具有压迫性，总体而言对她不利。",
