    topic_zh: "合同法：合同条款",
    concept: "Exclusion Clauses - 'Four Corners' Rule",
    concept_zh: "免责条款 - '四角'规则",
    case: "Council of the City of Sydney v West (1965); Thomas National Transport (Melbourne) Pty Ltd v May & Baker (Australia) Pty Ltd (1966)",
    principle: "An exclusion clause generally does not protect a party from liability for acts done outside the 'four corners' (scope or objects) of the contract. If a party acts in a way not authorised or contemplated by the contract, they may not be able to rely on the clause.",
    principle_zh: "免责条款通常不能保护一方免于承担在合同“四角”（范围或目标）之外所实施行为的责任。如果一方的行为方式并非合同授权或预期的方式，则其可能无法依赖该条款。",
    summary: "In Sydney v West, releasing a car to an unauthorised person was outside the contract's scope. In Thomas National Transport v May & Baker, a carrier deviating from the agreed route and storing goods in an unauthorised way was outside the 'four corners', so the exclusion clause did not apply to damage resulting from that deviation.",
    summary_zh: "在Sydney v West案中，将汽车交给未经授权的人超出了合同范围。在Thomas National Transport v May & Baker案中，承运人偏离约定路线并以未经授权的方式储存货物超出了“四角”范围，因此免责条款不适用于因此偏离造成的损害。",
    scaffold: "The act of [Party A] in [describe conduct] may be outside the 'four corners' of the contract. If so, under the principle in Council of the City of Sydney v West, the exclusion clause would not protect them from liability for [loss/damage].",
    scaffold_zh: "[当事人A]在[描述行为]中的行为可能超出了合同的“四角”范围。如果是这样，根据Council of the City of Sydney v West案的原则，免责条款将不能保护他们免于承担[损失/损害]的责任。",
