    case: "White v John Warwick & Co. Ltd [1953]",
    principle: "If an exclusion clause is ambiguous, it will be construed 'contra proferentem' – that is, strictly against the party who drafted it and is seeking to rely on it. The interpretation most favourable to the other party will be adopted.",
